<p>In this post, we'll be using keyness to tease apart different kinds of crosswordese/bad fill. For more information on keyness, check out Costas Gabrielatos's phenomenal chapter <a href="https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/227092349.pdf">[REF]</a> in Corpus Approaches to Discourse <a href="https://books.google.com/books/about/Corpus_Approaches_to_Discourse.html?id=-M1JDwAAQBAJ">[REF]</a>, edited by Charlotte Taylor and Anna Marchi. I owe pretty much everything in this post to Gabrielatos's explanation. The implementation is all my own; if you're looking to do something similar, I got a lot of help from <a href="http://ucrel.lancs.ac.uk/llwizard.html">this log-likelihood wizard</a> put out by Paul Rayson and UCREL at Lancaster University, as well as <a href="https://alvinntnu.github.io/NTNU_ENC2036_LECTURES/keyword-analysis.html">this chapter</a> from Alvin Chen's National Taiwan Normal University course on corpus linguistics.</p>

<h3>Difference in Relative Frequencies</h3>

<p>So-called <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crosswordese">crosswordese</a> and <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/13/crosswords/how-to-make-a-crossword-fill.html#:~:text=bad%20fill">bad fill</a> plague many regular crosswords, and the NYT puzzle is no exception. But what <em>is</em> crosswordese? What makes certain words feel a little cheesy or unfair?</p>

<p>We took a look at raw answer frequency in the <a href="/common-answers-and-word-length">post about about word length</a>. But crosswordese is a little different. To isolate that feeling of unfairness, we have to compare crossword answers to normal english. Words that are really common in crosswords but relatively rare in normal english, those are the ones we roll our eyes at. The gap between how common a word is in crosswords and how common it is in normal enligh is its difference in relative frequency.</p>

<p>A note about the reference corpus: I'm using a frequency list of <a href="https://github.com/IlyaSemenov/wikipedia-word-frequency">english words from wikipedia articles</a> scraped in 2019. It'll produce different results than, say, a corpus of newspaper articles or of science fiction novels. Likely its style is pretty formal but with a lot of variation. It'll also probably skew towards people, places, institutions, acronyms, and in general the kind of thing you'd write a wikipedia article about. Anyway, enough throat clearing. Let's look at the numbers:</p>

