<p>The table shows words with large differences in relative frequency. Mostly they're grammatically useful words like articles, conjunctions, and prepositions. We should've expected as much. These are words that show up all over the place in normal english, but don't make very good crossword answers. Crossword answers don't really connect gramatically in the same way english words do, and anyway a lot of these would be really hard to clue. There are also a couple of two-letter words that <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/puzzles/submissions/crossword">according to the Times' rules</a> aren't allowed to be crossword answers.</p>

<p>Right now the table is only showing common english words. You can tell because they have <em>negative</em> values in the "differences in relative frequencies" column. What we care about are words that have a <em>positive</em> value, which you can see by checking the "only positive values" box and reloading the data. A group of likely crosswordese suspects pops right up: three-to-four-letters, vowel-heavy.</p>

<p>As an aside, you might think words like ERA that show up semi-medium-often-ish in normal english would have a lower relative frequency difference. In fact, ERA still tops our list. That's because word frequency is nonlinear. The most frequent words are disproportionately more common than less frequent words. If ERA is the most common crossword answer but only, say, the 1000<sup>th</sup> most common english word, its crossword relative frequency will dwarf its english relative frequency. Check out <a href="">the post on Zipf's law</a> for more!</p>

<h3>Keyness</h3>

<p>We have a good guess about crosswordese, but it's not the full story. For a more complete picture, we need a more complex metric. Keyness combines <strong>effect-size</strong> measures, which tell us about how big a difference there is between two corpora, with <strong>statistical measures</strong>, which tell us how reliable that difference is. A big difference doesn't mean much if it happened by chance. Then again, a statistically significant usage pattern isn't worth looking at unless it's interesting too.</p>

