<p>What does it all mean? Well, "log ratio" and "difference coefficient" are effect-size metrics. For every point of log ratio, a word appears (relatively) twice as many times in one corpus or the other. A log ratio of 14 means a word is about 16,000 times as common. "Difference coefficient" is the same as the difference in relative frequencies from earlier, only normalized by the combined relative frequencies (so, difference over sum). Normalizing is helpful because it lets us see past the most common words in each corpus (again, Zipf's law). Then, "log likelihood G2" and "bayes factor" are statistical metrics. A strong G<sup>2</sup> value is around 19, and a value of 23 is overwhelming. A strong BIC or Bayes factor is around 6, and 10 is overwhelming. We're filtering out anything with a bayes factor <= 2.</p>

<p>What we're left with is a very different list of keywords. Most of them <em>aren't really english words at all</em> -- they're loanwords, abbreviations, phrases, etc. And weird ones at that! Brands like ELAL and EDYS, french words like ETES and ETRE, proper nouns like OHARE and RELEE (yikes), phrases like IBET, and double whammies like borrowed phrase ELNINO. Abbreviations like RTES. Jargon like ALIENEE (woof). Irregular uses of affixes like RETAG, ACMES, and ANEAR.</p>

<p>At its best, the grid quietly locks into place with a satisfying click. Around bad fill, though, the grid seems obviously forced. It's tiring to see the same words over and over again in the puzzle, but it's worse when those words are so irregular or obscure that you were never going to think of them without guessing from the crosses. If raw frequency difference showed us some of the more boring crosswordese answers, I think this analysis shows us some of the more egregious ones. Answers where you'd go "that's not a word!", or "EVENER!? Come on!". These, to me, are some of the real feel-bad answers.</p>

<h3>Cluing Keywords</h3>

<p>Bad fill is hard to clue. Disclaimer: this is a bit of a crackpot theory and I haven't put it into numbers yet. But I've noticed that some very common answers can be clued in a bunch of creative ways. ERA can be a time period, a baseball statistic, a proposed constitutional amendment, or even a laundry detergent. Keyword answers, on the other hand...well, check out the clues for ALIENEE:</p>

